{
  "schema_name": "eywa_node_response",
  "schema_version": "v1",
  "orchestration_decision": "delegate",
  "decision_notes": "The problem asks for the minimum Hamming weight of the product of a constant (2023) and an integer n. This is equivalent to finding the minimum number of ones in the binary representation of a multiple of 2023. This is a classic problem related to the order of 2 modulo the odd part of the number, or finding a power of 2 that is congruent to 1 modulo the odd part.",
  "helpers": [
    {
      "label": "prime_factorization_and_modular_analysis",
      "instructions": "Factorize 2023 into its prime components. Identify the odd part of 2023. Determine if there exists an n such that 2023*n is a power of 2, or more generally, find the smallest possible number of ones in the binary representation of a multiple of 2023 by examining the properties of the multiplicative group of integers modulo 2023."
    },
    {
      "label": "weight_search_and_verification",
      "instructions": "Test if k(n) = 1 is possible (this requires 2023 to be a power of 2, which it is not). Test if k(n) = 2 is possible by checking if there exist integers a and b such that 2^a + 2^b is a multiple of 2023. This is equivalent to checking if 2^a is congruent to -2^b modulo 2023, or 2^(a-b) is congruent to -1 modulo 2023 (if a > b). If not, test if k(n) = 3 is possible by checking if 2^a + 2^b + 2^c is a multiple of 2023."
    }
  ],
  "synthesis_brief": "The parent should first use the prime factorization to confirm 2023 is odd. Then, use the results from the weight search to determine the smallest integer k such that a sum of k powers of 2 is divisible by 2023. If the second helper finds that 2^x is congruent to -1 mod 2023 for some x, then k(n)=2. If not, check for k(n)=3 using the modular properties identified."
}

